sentence: If you live an urban life and never spend much time in rural areas or outer suburbs, you've likely never set foot in a Tractor Supply store.
But plenty of people are regulars atTractor Supply ( TSCO ), which boasts nearly 1,400 stores in 49 states.
As the company likes to say, its customers are living "the rural lifestyle."
Tractor Supply is the largest operator of rural lifestyle stores in the U.S.
It sells everything from animal feed, hay and pet supplies to power tools, riding mowers, fencing and work clothes and boots.
"They sell needs as opposed to wants," said analyst David Magee of investment bank SunTrust Robinson Humphrey.
Most of Tractor Supply's customers are hobby farmers or hobby ranchers -- "self-reliants," as Tractor Supply has put it.
Common traits: they own land, animals and machinery.
Less than 10% of customers are full-time production farmers or ranchers, the company says.
"I can't think of another publicly traded company focused on this consumer," said Nomura Securities analyst Jessica Schoen Mace.
Stores have "loyal customers who keep coming back," she said.
The company was founded in 1938 as a mail-order catalog featuring tractor parts for farmers.

Farm stores gradually opened, but it wasn't until the early 2000s that management had an epiphany: they realized that stores were serving the "rural lifestyle" customer more than the farmer and rancher.
"It gave us a license to adjust our assortment and give us a much broader reach," said Chief Financial Officer Anthony Crudele.
Stores carry "a unique collection of products" that would otherwise take customers several trips to other retailers to find, Magee says.

Those other stores range from big-box retailers such asWal-Mart ( WMT ),Home Depot ( HD ) andLowe's ( LOW ) -- which usually require longer drives -- to local and regional feed-supply stores, as well as pet-supply chains likePetSmart ( PETM ).
But not all of those stores carry everything that a Tractor Supply customer may need.
Home Depot might have fencing, but not the kind suitable for containing cattle or horses.
Tractor Supply has been growing its store base around 8% a year.
Its goal: 2,100 stores.
In Q3, it opened 30 new stores.
It's aiming to expand in Western states, which are underpenetrated.
Key target markets include New Mexico, Colorado, Utah and Southern California, Crudele says.
A new distribution center in Arizona will open later this year.
At an average 15,500 square feet, Tractor Supply stores are much smaller than Wal-Mart, Home Depot and Lowe's.
Their smaller size is viewed as a selling point: customers don't have to walk far to find what they want.
And a smaller box can be more versatile when the company is looking for real estate sites to lease, Magee says.
Analysts say that customers don't seem to mind Tractor Supply's relatively higher prices, because products are of high quality.
A company spokeswoman points out that Wal-Mart's highest-price work boot is around $90, "and that would be an opening price point for us.
Ours is better quality but fairly priced, and that resonates with our customers."
Though items are not usually on sale, limited promotions are held throughout the year.
"We call it everyday value pricing, so you don't have to wait for a sale," Crudele said.
"We're not going to lead prices down.
We want to win on customer service and convenience."
Tractor Supply customers have the discretionary income to support their purchases.
They live in areas below the national average cost of living yet make incomes higher than the national average.
Since 2010, Tractor Supply revenue has grown 12% on a compounded annual basis, while per-share earnings have grown 28% on average.
Revenue in Q3 rose 12.6% to $1.36 billion.
Revenue should tally at nearly $5.7 billion for 2014 and $6.3 billion in 2015, according to analysts polled by Thomson Reuters.
That's up from $2 billion in 2005.
But earnings have been slowing recently.
Analyst consensus calls for a 13% gain in 2014, down from 22% growth in 2013 and 26% in 2012.
"As we came out of the recession, there was pent-up demand," Crudele said, adding that the company's current mid-teens annual earnings growth is still "pretty solid growth."
Same-store sales in the third quarter jumped a higher-than-expected 5.6%.

That sales growth -- and the company's better-than-expected earnings growth of 20% to 55 cents per share -- sent Tractor Supply stock soaring nearly 16%, to 71, on Oct. 23 after results were reported.
Shares now trade near 77.
Comparable-store gains in the quarter were driven by gains in traffic and ticket size, the company said.
Comparable-store transactions increased 3.3%, and the average ticket rose 2.2% to $43.75.
But deflation, principally in livestock feed, bird feed, lubricants and fencing, partially offset the favorable comparables.
Gross margin in Q3 fell slightly, to 34.1% from 34.4% a year earlier.
Crudele blamed higher freight costs to distant Western markets and a larger mix of sales of lower-margin big-ticket items.
But Tractor Supply's operating margin rose to 8.9% of sales from 8.4% a year earlier.
Operating margins have improved the last few years as sales have moved higher.
Tractor Supply raised its fiscal 2014 sales and earnings outlook to the high end of its previously provided range.
It expects net sales of $5.62-$5.70 billion, 2.5%-4% in comparable store sales growth and earnings per share of $2.54-$2.62, up from 2013's $2.32.
Fourth-quarter results will likely benefit from seasonably cold weather, though comparisons will be tough against last year's cold snap.
As Mace wrote in a recent report, "the colder the better" for heating, clothing and outwear categories, unless it gets too cold to venture out.
Tractor Supply gets bumps from seasonal demand, such as spring planting season and the need for cold-weather gear in winter.
Third-quarter sales benefited from an extended spring selling season into early September.

Recalling last year's polar vortex, JPMorgan analyst Christopher Horvers pointed out that Tractor Supply's September sales also benefited from early purchases of home heating, snow removal products and winter apparel.
Tractor Supply "purposefully leaned its assortment into this trend in anticipation of consumers not wanting to be left out in the cold again this winter," Horvers wrote in December.
"Similar factors, given the cold snap and significant snow coverage in the U.S.," drove impressive November results at Home Depot and Lowe's.
